A `void*` is for storing the `address` that holds any kind of sized type. It is not meant for storing integer values which do not symbolize an address of memory.

If you want to store multiple differently sized types in a single type without a pointer, consider using an enum compound type. This type would use two 32 bit integers to work on a 32bit system.

    enum 32_or_64_int_t {
          UINT32_TYPE,
          UINT64_TYPE
    };
    
    struct 64_int_t {
        uint32_t value[2];
        enum 32_or_64_int_t type;
    };

You would still need to implement 64bit arithmetic and other operations using this approach if you wanted to do more then just storage it.

